          "body": "The chapter closes with one of the New Testament's most theologically dense benedictions. *The God of peace* — covenant peace, the *shalom* of restored relationship — *brought up from the dead the great Shepherd of the sheep, through the blood of the eternal covenant, even Jesus our Lord*. Every major theme of the letter is gathered: God's covenant initiative, the resurrection of Christ (named explicitly for the first and only time in Hebrews here), the *blood* that ratifies the new arrangement, and the *eternal* (not Sinai-temporary) character of that covenant. The doxological aim — *equip you in every good thing to do His will, working in us that which is pleasing in His sight* — gathers the chapter's ethical imperatives back into divine enablement. The believer does not produce obedience under threat; God *works in us* what pleases Him through Jesus Christ. The doxology *to whom be the glory forever and ever* (v.21) ascribes to Christ what only God receives. The letter that argued the Son's deity from chapter 1 confirms it in worship at chapter 13."
